{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Implementing Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) Linear Regression\n","\n","Linear regression can be understood as finding the best-fitting straight line through a set of training data. This is achieved using the **Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)** method, which estimates the parameters of the regression line by minimizing the sum of the squared vertical distances (residuals) between the training examples and the line.\n","\n","## 1. Regression via Gradient Descent (Theoretical Background)\n","\n","We can solve for the regression parameters using optimization algorithms like **Gradient Descent (GD)**. This approach is mathematically identical to the Adaptive Linear Neuron (Adaline), but without the threshold function, allowing for continuous target values instead of class labels.\n","\n","The loss function used for OLS is the **Mean Squared Error (MSE)**:\n","\n","$$L(\\mathbf{w}, b) = \\frac{1}{2n} \\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y^{(i)} - \\hat{y}^{(i)})^2$$\n","\n","Here, $\\hat{y}$ is the predicted value $\\hat{y} = \\mathbf{w}^T\\mathbf{x} + b$. The term $\\frac{1}{2}$ is included merely for convenience when deriving the gradient update rule."],"metadata":{"id":"389PGJn534Mg"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Object-Oriented Implementation\n","\n","Below is the implementation of a linear regression model using gradient descent from scratch."],"metadata":{"id":"VYKez8G35off"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import numpy as np\n","\n","class LinearRegressionGD:\n","    def __init__(self, eta=0.01, n_iter=50, random_state=1):\n","        self.eta = eta\n","        self.n_iter = n_iter\n","        self.random_state = random_state\n","\n","    def fit(self, X, y):\n","        rgen = np.random.RandomState(self.random_state)\n","        self.w_ = rgen.normal(loc=0.0, scale=0.01, size=X.shape[1])\n","        self.b_ = np.array([0.])\n","        self.losses_ = []\n","\n","        for i in range(self.n_iter):\n","            output = self.net_input(X)\n","            errors = (y - output)\n","            self.w_ += self.eta * 2.0 * X.T.dot(errors) / X.shape[0]\n","            self.b_ += self.eta * 2.0 * errors.mean()\n","            loss = (errors**2).mean()\n","            self.losses_.append(loss)\n","        return self\n","\n","    def net_input(self, X):\n","        return np.dot(X, self.w_) + self.b_\n","\n","    def predict(self, X):\n","        return self.net_input(X)"],"outputs":[],"execution_count":4,"metadata":{"id":"OdcK1LYV34Mk","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856450398,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":55,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 2. Training the Model and Visualizing Results\n","\n","To see the model in action, we train it using a dataset (e.g., the Ames Housing dataset), predicting `SalePrice` based on `Gr Liv Area` (living area in square feet). Standardizing variables beforehand helps the Gradient Descent algorithm converge faster.\n","\n","### Data Preparation and Model Fitting"],"metadata":{"id":"JpYDtmaH34Mm"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import pandas as pd\n","\n","# Define the subset of columns to use\n","columns = ['Gr Liv Area', 'SalePrice']\n","\n","# Load the dataset\n","df = pd.read_csv('http://jse.amstat.org/v19n3/decock/AmesHousing.txt',\n","                 sep='\\t',\n","                 usecols=columns)"],"metadata":{"id":"FS5aOXh56bNh","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856450885,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":491,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}}},"execution_count":5,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n","\n","X = df[['Gr Liv Area']].values\n","y = df['SalePrice'].values\n","\n","sc_x = StandardScaler()\n","sc_y = StandardScaler()\n","\n","X_std = sc_x.fit_transform(X)\n","y_std = sc_y.fit_transform(y[:, np.newaxis]).flatten()\n","\n","lr = LinearRegressionGD(eta=0.1)\n","lr.fit(X_std, y_std)"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["<__main__.LinearRegressionGD at 0x785c289db2f0>"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":6}],"execution_count":6,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"0ZihPnef34Mm","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856450917,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":17,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"9fd68ea7-7e3c-4e19-c8bc-9fcc0ccf5385"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["*(Note: `np.newaxis` and `flatten()` are workarounds because scikit-learn's `StandardScaler` expects 2D arrays.)*\n","\n","### Plotting Convergence\n","\n","It is good practice to plot the loss as a function of the number of epochs to ensure the algorithm has converged to a global loss minimum."],"metadata":{"id":"ECxJ_dmk34Mm"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plt.plot(range(1, lr.n_iter+1), lr.losses_)\n","plt.ylabel('MSE')\n","plt.xlabel('Epoch')\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":7,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":454},"id":"tDI-JQpB34Mn","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856451130,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":202,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"a4700854-8289-48b3-d15f-95c3fac1cec1"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Visualizing the Regression Line"],"metadata":{"id":"STD4yF7434Mn"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["def lin_regplot(X, y, model):\n","    plt.scatter(X, y, c='steelblue', edgecolor='white', s=70)\n","    plt.plot(X, model.predict(X), color='black', lw=2)\n","\n","lin_regplot(X_std, y_std, lr)\n","plt.xlabel('Living area above ground (standardized)')\n","plt.ylabel('Sale price (standardized)')\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":8,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"70d9i5IR34Mo","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856451402,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":270,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"86d71a57-d1c4-48fa-e8c8-a95078cdc294"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Scaling Predictions Back to Original Values\n","\n","If we need to report predicted outcomes in their original scale (e.g., U.S. dollars), we can use the `inverse_transform` method:"],"metadata":{"id":"HWdFzlss34Mo"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Predicting the price of a 2,500 sq ft house\n","feature_std = sc_x.transform(np.array([[2500]]))\n","target_std = lr.predict(feature_std)\n","target_reverted = sc_y.inverse_transform(target_std.reshape(-1, 1))\n","\n","print(f'Sales price: ${target_reverted.flatten()[0]:.2f}')\n","# Expected Output: Sales price: $292507.07\n","\n","print(f'Slope: {lr.w_[0]:.3f}')\n","print(f'Intercept: {lr.b_[0]:.3f}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Sales price: $292523.08\n","Slope: 0.707\n","Intercept: -0.000\n"]}],"execution_count":9,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"CikkNLWS34Mo","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856451403,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":19,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"e36ec4fc-d40a-4eb8-b15c-ec514a2bbbca"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 3. Implementation via Scikit-Learn\n","\n","For real-world applications, `scikit-learn` provides highly optimized, non-iterative estimator implementations using the `SciPy` least squares function (which utilizes LAPACK). Because it doesn't rely on Gradient Descent, standardization is not strictly required."],"metadata":{"id":"NBx7JnNm34Mp"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n","\n","slr = LinearRegression()\n","slr.fit(X, y)\n","y_pred = slr.predict(X)\n","\n","print(f'Slope: {slr.coef_[0]:.3f}')\n","print(f'Intercept: {slr.intercept_:.3f}')\n","\n","# Plotting the scikit-learn results\n","lin_regplot(X, y, slr)\n","plt.xlabel('Living area above ground in square feet')\n","plt.ylabel('Sale price in U.S. dollars')\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Slope: 111.694\n","Intercept: 13289.634\n"]},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":10,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":522},"id":"Dw6DCwCM34Mp","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856451905,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":513,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"ca65c863-a804-417d-ddf6-3b38c95b2f42"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## 4. Analytical (Closed-Form) Solution\n","\n","Alternatively, linear regression can be solved analytically using a closed-form solution known as the **Normal Equation**:\n","\n","$$\\mathbf{w} = (\\mathbf{X}^T\\mathbf{X})^{-1}\\mathbf{X}^T\\mathbf{y}$$\n","\n","### Numpy Implementation"],"metadata":{"id":"harYhQBM34Mp"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["# Adding a column vector of \"ones\" for the bias unit\n","Xb = np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0], 1)), X))\n","w = np.zeros(X.shape[1])\n","z = np.linalg.inv(np.dot(Xb.T, Xb))\n","w = np.dot(z, np.dot(Xb.T, y))\n","\n","print(f'Slope: {w[1]:.3f}')\n","print(f'Intercept: {w[0]:.3f}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Slope: 111.694\n","Intercept: 13289.634\n"]}],"execution_count":11,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"rF0z2gAg34Mp","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781856451917,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":11,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"3ba27c73-dcb6-43ea-e8ba-ba46ac14ba81"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Pros & Cons of the Analytical Method:**\n","\n","* **Advantage:** It guarantees finding the optimal optimal solution analytically without needing to define a learning rate or iterate.\n","* **Disadvantage:** It is computationally expensive for large datasets because calculating the inverse of a matrix is a heavy operation. Additionally, the matrix may be singular (non-invertible) under certain conditions."],"metadata":{"id":"7Sp2lQpP34Mp"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}